(STEP and PDES) 126 678.67 T
0 12 Q
0.12 (STEP is the emerging international Standard for the Exchange of Product Model Data) 126 658 P
7.3 (being developed under the auspices of the International Organization for) 126 644 P
(Standardization \050ISO\051.) 126 630 T
-0.19 (PDES is the acronym for Product Data Exchange using STEP. It is the U. S. activity in) 126 610 P
-0.69 (support of STEP. PDES is being furthered in the United States by several organizations.) 126 596 P
2.78 (The IGES/PDES Organization \050IPO\051 is a voluntary standards organization which) 126 582 P
0.12 (participates in developing the STEP standards. Two of the many IPO/ISO committees) 126 568 P
2.94 (helping develop STEP are the Form Features Committee and the Manufacturing) 126 554 P
-0.25 (Technology Committee. PDES, Inc. is a consortium of major companies which has the) 126 540 P
0.31 (goal of accelerating the implementation of PDES. The National Institute of Standards) 126 526 P
1.88 (and Technology \050NIST\051 has established a National PDES Testbed. The Testbed is) 126 512 P
0.6 (funded by the Computer-aided Acquisition and Logistic Support \050CALS\051 program of) 126 498 P
(the Office of the Secretary of Defense.) 126 484 T
2.78 (Data descriptions are handled in STEP by defining an information model in the) 126 464 P
0.14 (EXPRESS data modeling language [Schenck90, Spiby91] for each type of data that is) 126 450 P
1.12 (needed. Once an information model is in place, data representing a specific product) 126 436 P
1.2 (may be put into a computer or on paper according to the rules in STEP Part 21 for) 126 422 P
4.75 (mapping EXPRESS to a STEP physical file [Altemueller88a, Altemueller88b,) 126 408 P
0.31 (VanMaanen91]. The data section of a STEP physical file normally consists wholly of) 126 394 P
(instances of data entities of the sort made available by the EXPRESS model.) 126 380 T
1 14 Q
(1.2) 72 352.67 T
(MRSEVs) 126 352.67 T
0 12 Q
0.15 (In machining a metal part, it is sometimes feasible to use features on the design of the) 126 332 P
-0.33 (part to determine what material to machine away in order to make the part from a piece) 126 318 P
2.62 (of raw stock or a partially machined workpiece. Very often, however, it will be) 126 304 P
1.67 (desirable to machine the workpiece so that it has temporary features which do not) 126 290 P
-0.18 (appear on the design, or which do not correspond exactly to design features. To handle) 126 276 P
0.69 (this situation, it is useful to have a method for describing the shape of material to be) 126 262 P
1.34 (removed by machining operations. Shapes of volumes to be removed are generated) 126 248 P
0.92 (during process planning and used for NC-programming. The need for these material) 126 234 P
2.25 (removal volume shapes was cited in a document,) 126 220 P
