(3) 72 708 T
(A Library of MRSEVs for 3-Axis Machining) 126 708 T
0 12 Q
1.96 (This section defines a library of MRSEVs for use with process plans for a 3-axis) 126 680 P
2.07 (machining center. This could be either a vertical-spindle machine or a horizontal-) 126 666 P
(spindle machine. Both types typically perform the same operations.) 126 652 T
1 14 Q
(3.1) 72 624.67 T
(Nature of MRSEVs in Library) 126 624.67 T
0 12 Q
0.21 (At the elemental move level, the more capable 3-axis machining centers can drive the) 126 604 P
0.91 (tip of a cutting tool in only three distinct trajectories: \050i\051 a straight line between two) 126 590 P
-0.68 (points in 3-dimensions, \050ii\051 an arc of a circle \050or a complete circle\051 whose axis is parallel) 126 576 P
-0.1 (to one of the three principal axes of the machine, or \050iii\051 an arc of a helix whose axis is) 126 562 P
-0.26 (parallel to one of the three principal axes of the machine. The library includes MRSEV) 126 548 P
0.51 (types \050holes, ramps, and grooves\051 for representing the swept volumes created when a) 126 534 P
1.21 (cutter whose spinning shape is a cylinder with either a flat end or a rounded end is) 126 520 P
0.38 (driven along any of those three trajectories - with the top of the swept volume cut off) 126 506 P
0.2 (flat, and with the limitation that the axis of a circular or helical arc must be parallel to) 126 492 P
(the axis of the cutter.) 126 478 T
-0.69 (At a higher level, certain more complex shapes are commonly found on machined parts.) 126 458 P
2.61 (These include complex grooves, pockets, steps, and exterior profiles. The library) 126 444 P
0.03 (provides shapes for all of these. It is intended that the \322pocket\323 MRSEVs defined here) 126 430 P
0.27 (be used for producing not only what is usually called a pocket, but also for producing) 126 416 P
0.65 (what are usually called steps and exterior profiles and for removing what are usually) 126 402 P
(called slabs.) 126 388 T
0.36 (All the MRSEVs are to be construed as closed volumes. The tops of all MRSEVs are) 126 368 P
0.31 (to be construed as being planar. Each type of MRSEV has a native coordinate system) 126 354 P
0.34 (attached to it. When an instance of a MRSEV is built, the native coordinate system is) 126 340 P
(located with respect to some parent coordinate system by a locator.) 126 326 T
1 14 Q
(3.2) 72 298.67 T
(Description Methods) 126 298.67 T
0 12 Q
-0.71 (The library of MRSEVs is described here as a hierarchy of entity types. Each entity type) 126 278 P
0.22 (has a number of attributes. The attributes have values which must be of some specific) 126 264 P
-0.15 (data type \050single instances or sets of: a real number, a string, a choice of one of a set of) 126 250 P
-0.41 (tokens, or an entity type\051. Some attributes are optional. Describing an optional attribute) 126 236 P
0.05 (as \322omitted\323 in this section should be interpreted as meaning the same thing as having) 126 222 P
1.98 (a value for the attribute which is a null value. An entity may have subtypes. The) 126 208 P
-0.23 (subtypes inherit all the attributes of the parent types and may have additional attributes) 126 194 P
0.62 (of their own. Only entity types which do not have subtypes can be used as MRSEVs) 126 180 P
1.64 (referenced by process plans. This description method is conceptually identical to a) 126 166 P
0.81 (subset of EXPRESS, but we are not using EXPRESS syntax in this section, and any) 126 152 P
(other language that includes the elements just described could be used.) 126 138 T
3.57 (Two types of figures are used in this section: \050i\051 MRSEV hierarchies and \050ii\051) 126 118 P
0.5 (descriptions of individual MRSEV types. In many cases, restrictions on the values of) 126 104 P
2.31 (attributes are required. These restrictions do not appear in the hierarchies but are) 126 90 P
(included in the individual descriptions.) 126 76 T
