5.23 (An edge_cut is the shape resulting from sweeping a right triangle along a) 126 692 P
-0.61 (general_profile path while keeping the triangle perpendicular to the path. One leg of the) 126 678 P
-0.68 (triangle is kept parallel to the plane of the profile, and the other leg is kept perpendicular) 126 664 P
-0.38 (to the plane. The hypotenuse of the triangle may be replaced by an arc of a circle which) 126 650 P
(curves toward the right angle.) 126 636 T
2.34 (There are two subtypes of edge_cut, \322edge_flat\323, in which the hypotenuse of the) 126 616 P
-0.71 (triangle is kept as a straight line, and \322edge_round\323, in which the hypotenuse is replaced) 126 602 P
(by an arc of a circle.) 126 588 T
0.36 (An edge_cut is used for flattening or rounding an edge of a workpiece. Typically this) 126 568 P
1.36 (is done with a rounder or chamfer tool in a rounding or chamfering operation. The) 126 554 P
0.65 (edge_cut could also be used with a countersinking operation, but using a hole with a) 126 540 P
(conical end is preferable.) 126 526 T
0.21 (Edge-cuts and edge-blends are both treated as blends in most solid modelers, but they) 126 506 P
1.71 (are quite different in machining, where the names \322chamfer\323 and \322fillet\323 are more) 126 492 P
1.74 (commonly used. An edge_blend leaves extra material, while an edge_cut indicates) 126 478 P
0.79 (material to be removed. An edge_blend is often made as its parent MRSEV is being) 126 464 P
2.31 (made, so edge_blends are represented as attributes of the parent feature. Usually,) 126 450 P
-0.04 (machining the parent MRSEV will leave an edge to which an edge_cut is applied later) 126 436 P
0.53 (in a separate operation. Edge_cuts can also be applied to outer edges of a workpiece,) 126 422 P
(where there may be no parent MRSEV.) 126 408 T
-0.12 (If the entire edge of a pocket is to have an edge_cut applied to it, the same profile used) 126 388 P
1.69 (to define the pocket can be used to define the edge_cut, so that little extra data is) 126 374 P
(required to define the edge_cut, once the pocket is defined.) 126 360 T
0.29 (The swept volume of an edge_cut and the method of describing the sweeping process) 126 340 P
-0.12 (are the same for an edge_cut as for a groove, except at the end of an edge_cut using an) 126 326 P
-0.64 (open profile, which is discussed below. The native coordinate system of the triangle has) 126 312 P
-0.27 (its origin at the corner of the triangle which has the right angle. One side of the triangle) 126 298 P
1.11 (lies on the minus-x axis and the other side lies on the minus-y axis. The coordinate) 126 284 P
-0.22 (system of the edge_cut itself is the coordinate system of its profile with a z-axis added.) 126 270 P
-0.19 (The prohibitions concerning right and left turns which apply to a groove will not apply) 126 250 P
0.12 (to an edge_cut. This is because during the machining of a groove, the cutter is usually) 126 236 P
-0.22 (surrounded by material, but during machining an edge_cut, the cutter is usually mostly) 126 222 P
0.85 (surrounded by air and can machine the edge_cut without gouging the part. Also, the) 126 208 P
-0.05 (volume swept by the cutter in making a groove is expected to be about the same as the) 126 194 P
-0.35 (volume of the groove, whereas the edge_cut volume is expected to be significantly less) 126 180 P
(than half the swept volume of the cutter that makes it.) 126 166 T
0.4 (If the profile of an edge_cut is open, there will be an addition to the swept volume of) 126 146 P
-0.66 (the triangle which differs from the additional volumes at the end of an open groove. The) 126 132 P
0.89 (additional volume at the end of the edge cut will always be a piece of a cone for an) 126 118 P
0.4 (edge_flat and a piece of cone minus a piece of torus for an edge_round, but the exact) 126 104 P
