2.31 (A prototype EXPRESS schema follows, which defines the subset of the MRSEV) 126 680 P
1.59 (library which is currently in use in the Off-Line Programming System, namely the) 126 666 P
3.04 (linear_sweep subtypes shown in Figure 2 \050holes and pockets\051. Only the \322mesa\323) 126 652 P
4.72 (subtypes of island shown in Figure 3 and only the \322replication\323 subtype of) 126 638 P
(mrsev_copy_method shown in Figure 4 are included.) 126 624 T
3.03 (This prototype uses the \322Tokyo\323 versions of the EXPRESS language, the Form) 126 604 P
0.57 (Features Information Model \050FFIM\051, the Geometry Model, and the Topology Model.) 126 590 P
1.07 (In a few cases, the FFIM has been assumed to have been modified slightly to solve) 126 576 P
-0.24 (technical problems in using it as a resource. In a few other cases, the EXPRESS \322map\323) 126 562 P
1.26 (facility has been used in an improper fashion, also to deal with technical problems.) 126 548 P
1.98 (Thus, this prototype is not in complete conformance with the Tokyo versions and) 126 534 P
0.05 (should be regarded only as being illustrative of how resource models might be used to) 126 520 P
(build application models in STEP.) 126 506 T
0.09 (Moreover, EXPRESS, the FFIM, the Geometry Model, and the Topology Model have) 126 486 P
1.08 (all changed since the Tokyo version. To put this prototype in conformance with the) 126 472 P
(current versions would require extensive revisions.) 126 458 T
1.36 (The general approach taken to building the prototype is to draw heavily on entities) 126 438 P
-0.03 (defined in the FFIM. EXPRESS provides the \322map\323 function for defining new entities) 126 424 P
0.67 (in terms of existing ones, and \322map\323 has been used as the principal link between the) 126 410 P
(FFIM and the prototype.) 126 396 T
0.91 (In some instances, the FFIM uses a general version of entity A in defining entity B,) 126 376 P
4.5 (while the prototype requires a specialized subtype S of entity A in defining) 126 362 P
0.49 (mrsev_volume type C which corresponds to FFIM entity B. In such cases, a \322where\323) 126 348 P
0.69 (clause is added to the mapping of B to C to identify the subtype S. For example, the) 126 334 P
4.47 (FFIM uses feature_sweep_path \050A\051 in defining in_out_feature_sweep \050B\051. The) 126 320 P
11.26 (prototype defines pocket \050C\051 as an in_out_feature_sweep where the) 126 306 P
(feature_sweep_path is a linear_feature_sweep_path \050S\051.) 126 292 T
1.93 (Because of the requirement of the FFIM that each form_feature be classified as a) 126 272 P
1.03 (depression, protrusion or passage, which is not desirable in the prototype, the FFIM) 126 258 P
3.1 (form_feature entity is not used in this prototype. Two hierarchical levels below) 126 244 P
2.72 (form_feature, the FFIM defines \322feature_volume\323. Feature_volumes exist without) 126 230 P
1.16 (regard to any parent part. Feature_volume is used in the prototype as the top of the) 126 216 P
(hierarchy of mrsev_volumes.) 126 202 T
1.34 (In the prototype, the \322primary_mrsev_volume\323 entity on Figure 2 is not used as an) 126 182 P
7.89 (intermediate subtype. The prototype has \322linear_sweep\323 \050under the name) 126 168 P
1.94 (\322feature_sweep\323 inherited from the FFIM\051 as a direct subtype of \322mrsev_volume\323) 126 154 P
(\050under the name \322feature_volume\323, also inherited from the FFIM\051.) 126 140 T
