(C) 72 708 T
(An Example of Using MRSEVs) 126 708 T
0 12 Q
1.81 (The Off-Line Programming System \050OLPS\051 developed at NIST between 1988 and) 126 680 P
2.34 (1990, is a system for generating NC-programs, in the context shown in Figure 1) 126 666 P
([Kramer91a]. OLPS uses all the MRSEV types defined in Appendix B.) 126 652 T
2.34 (Machining operations currently implemented in OLPS are: center-drill, twist-drill,) 126 632 P
0.06 (counterbore, rough-mill, finish-mill, initialize-plan, close-plan, and set0-corner. Many) 126 618 P
(other operations are defined but not yet implemented.) 126 604 T
1.49 (Some types of operations can use more than one type of MRSEV. Rough-mill and) 126 584 P
2.34 (finish-mill, for example, can refer to any of the four types of pockets defined in) 126 570 P
0.46 (Appendix B. On the other side of the coin, some types of MRSEVs can be named by) 126 556 P
-0.42 (many types of operations. Center-drill, twist-drill, and counterbore, for example, all act) 126 542 P
1.85 (on holes. If all three of those operations are required to make a single hole, three) 126 528 P
-0.76 (different MRSEV holes will normally be used, one for each operation. If the drilled hole) 126 514 P
1.07 (were nominally identical to the counterbored hole, however, only one MRSEV hole) 126 500 P
(would be required for the two operations.) 126 486 T
-0.05 (As shown in Figure 1, OLPS \050which is the \322NC-PROGRAMMING\323 box shown in the) 126 466 P
0.55 (figure\051 requires six kinds of input data, all of which are entered using STEP physical) 126 452 P
3.75 (files. The data for the design, the workpiece, and the fixture are in boundary) 126 438 P
0.06 (representation format using STEP geometry and topology entities. The process plan is) 126 424 P
0.28 (prepared using a schema for the ALPS language [Ray91] with added entities defining) 126 410 P
-0.63 (machining operations [Kramer91b]. MRSEV data is prepared according to the MRSEV) 126 396 P
-0.31 (schema in Appendix B, with the slight modification that real numbers are used in place) 126 382 P
3.12 (of independent_size_parameters. The setup file currently being used contains 18) 126 368 P
(specific STEP geometry entities.) 126 354 T
1.28 (OLPS includes its own STEP file reader but does not include an EXPRESS parser.) 126 334 P
-0.31 (Rather, it requires that information equivalent to the entity definitions in the schemas it) 126 320 P
(uses be entered in a LISP-readable database.) 126 306 T
1.72 (A part, named \322clevis2\323, that may be cut on a 3-axis machining center using NC-) 126 286 P
2.09 (programs written automatically by OLPS is shown in Figure C1. It requires three) 126 272 P
0.72 (fixturings. The entire process plan for the second fixturing is shown in Figure C2. A) 126 258 P
-0.27 (portion of the MRSEV file for the second fixturing is shown in Figure C3. The data for) 126 244 P
-0.4 (only three of the MRSEVs is shown in Figure C3, namely the MRSEVs whose pictures) 126 230 P
0.72 (are in Figures C4 and C5. The MRSEV named \322other_pocket31\323 is shown in Figure) 126 216 P
0.4 (C4, where the MRSEV is shown in heavy lines superimposed on a picture of the part) 126 202 P
-0.31 (\050light solid lines and the workpiece \050light dashed lines\051. Figure C5 shows the MRSEVs) 126 188 P
(named \322rectangular_pocket23\323 and \322hole30\323 in a similar view.) 126 174 T
0.08 (The part pictures in the figures are screen images from OLPS. The pictures show wire) 126 154 P
-0.51 (frame drawings of the edges of the objects. A STEP format boundary representation for) 126 140 P
(each MRSEV is generated automatically by OLPS in order to do the drawing.) 126 126 T
FMENDPAGE
